<TEXT>
ralfone a 5yearold orangutan 
who escaped from a crate in paris three years ago and led 
authorities to a dozen other smuggled primates is returning to the 
malaysian island of borneo 
the reddish ape was handed to malaysias science technology and 
environment minister stephen yong on tuesday in a brief ceremony 
witnessed by five association of southeast asian nations 
environment ministers who had just ended a regional conference in 
kuala lumpur 
she will be taken to the sepilok orangutan sanctuary in 
sandakan 1030 miles east of kuala lumpur on borneo island then 
returned to the jungle after about six months of rehabilitation 
officials said 
mohamed khir johari malaysian president of the world wide fund 
for nature said officials of the organization and the french 
government seized ralfone at the paris airport in may 1987 
the ape with another orangutan and 11 macaque monkeys 
apparently was headed for mexico all the animals were in poor 
health and had received little or no food and water khir said 
how she was smuggled remains a mystery khir said 
ralfones escape led to the discovery of the other animals he 
said the second orangutan will remain in the antwerp zoo in 
belgium because it has become accustomed to captivity and the 
monkeys have been sent to the paris zoo he said 
orangutans live wild only in the jungles of borneo and sumatra 
where ther are an estimated 30000 of them 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

