<DOCNO> AP900620-0004 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
david johnny has witnessed so many 
atrocities in liberias war including seeing the bulletriddled 
bodies of family members that his eyes are blank and his face 
shows no emotion as he recounts them 
his tragedy is one of thousands in a nearly 6monthold war 
whose chief victims are civilians targeted by both sides because of 
their tribal affiliations 
the horrors for johnny 18 began two weeks ago when rebels 
attacked the village near the bong iron ore mine where he attended 
boarding school 
they start killing the soldier people there just spraying 
them with their guns in one group they gunned i saw at least 20 
soldiers die he said in an interview at a church mission here 
where he was given shelter and reunited with a brother 
then they surrounded the compound for mandingos and krahns and 
just started cutting the peoples throats with the knives from 
their guns 
johnny and a school friend who also witnessed the killings are 
members of the gio tribe many rebels also are gios and have been 
slaughtering civilians of president samuel does krahn tribe and 
mandingos whom the rebels accuse of enriching themselves during 
does 10year rule 
there are no reports of rebels killing gio or mano people but 
because many of them support the guerrillas they have become the 
target of government soldiers 
johnny said he and his friend fled into the forest and hid there 
for two days living on nuts and leaves before making their way 30 
miles south to grimes farm a village near the town of kakata where 
his parents lived 
they spent the night with johnnys father who is a subsistence 
farmer and retired rubber plantation worker and his mother and two 
sisters 
the next morning june 9 the two friends were out picking pine 
nuts for the family when then heard gunfire johnny said 
we waited until the shooting stopped then tried to creep into 
the village through the bushes but the soldiers spied us and fired 
at us touching me with a bullet he said displaying a graze on 
his hip 
my friend hauled me by the hand and dragged me into the 
forest and we hide there for two days in fear 
when they crept out and went back to the family hut johnny 
found the bodies of his father and two sisters his mother was 
missing 
the friends spent another two days working their way through the 
bush to the village of cowway where johnnys younger brother 
joseph 15 was staying but before they got there the village was 
attacked 
joseph picked up the story men with guns came shooting they 
killed many people and hurt others i dont know what happened to 
the woman i was staying with 
joseph said the attackers wore uniforms but did not know 
whether they were rebels or government soldiers adults who came 
from the same village said only gios lived there and that the 
killers were does soldiers 
joseph said he walked for almost three days until he got to 
monrovia where he sought shelter at don bosco polytechnic one of 
six church missions sheltering mano and gio people fearing attacks 
by soldiers 
when david reached cowway he was told his brother had gone to a 
church in monrovia the brothers were reunited last week 
they got some good news during the weekend a family friend told 
them their mother musu johnny was alive she had been seriously 
wounded in the grimes farm attack and was being treated at kakata 
hospital 
the town is behind rebel lines and there was no way for the 
brothers to check the report 
they are among about 250000 people who have fled the fighting 
many to neighboring countries 
about 600 sleep on mats in classrooms at don bosco a technical 
and business school run by the salesian roman catholic priests who 
are based in stockton england 
the schools dean the rev brian jerstice has been busy 
organizing classroom instruction for the many refugee children 
making sure the makeshift clinic has enough staff and medication 
distributing donated clothing and worrying about food supplies and 
sanitary conditions 
we thought we could put up 200 people now there are 600 
crowded here and there is no more sleeping space jerstice said 
the hardest part is having to turn people away 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

