<DOCNO> AP900620-0005 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
despite the global thaw in eastwest 
relations the cold war is chilling efforts to end angolas 15year 
civil war 
billions of dollars worth of soviet and us weapons have kept 
the war going between the marxist government and jonas savimbis 
unita rebels 
though the superpowers now want to spend less on regional 
conflicts neither seems willing to see its client lose the 
struggle for power in one of africas potentially richest nations 
when portuguese colonizers pulled out in 1975 a tribalbased 
conflict between northern central and southern angolans soon 
became a surrogate war as the kremlin battled the west for 
influence in southern africa 
some 50000 cuban soldiers and the best red army hardware were 
sent to help the popular movement for the liberation of angola 
mpla which declared independence and became the government in 
luanda 
most western nations except the united states israel and south 
africa recognized the mpla government headed by agostinho neto 
south africa allied its army with unita the national union for the 
total independence of angola 
south african aid to the rebels officially ended with regional 
peace accords signed by angola and cuba in december 1988 but unita 
still receives us military assistance thought to be 50 million 
this fiscal year 
cuba has already sent home more than 33000 soldiers under the 
agreement but western estimates put continuing soviet support at 
between 600 million and 15 billion a year 
despite efforts by african and european diplomats and a letter 
from us congressmen to president bush urging him to raise the 
angolan issue with president mikhail s gorbachev at their recent 
summit there is still superpower involvement 
backing continues although its getting much more difficult 
to support aid increases to savimbi in the current eastwest 
climate said one western official speaking on the condition of 
anonymity 
secretary of state james a baker iii said last week that us 
supplies might be cut off if luanda agrees to free and fair 
elections but the bush administration has since asked congress to 
earmark an added 10 to 15 million a year for the rebels 
congressional sources say the rebels would use some of the money 
to buy hawk antiaircraft missiles adding to an arsenal of 
shoulderfired stinger rockets 
yuri yukalov a leading kremlin diplomat specializing in 
southern africa recently pledged that arms supplies to luanda 
would go on as long as the war continues according to portuguese 
news reports 
an article from a recent edition of the soviet weekly new times 
published in the portuguese media said that between 600 and 1000 
soviet military advisers are still in angola though not actively 
involved in the war 
foreign minister pedro de castro van dunem of angola has 
criticized south africa and the united states for continuing to 
funnel unita aid through zaire 
president mobutu sese seko of zaire brought savimbi and 
president jose eduardo dos santos together for an initial truce 
last june 22 at gbadolite but the ceasefire collapsed days later 
in confusion over peace terms 
government military campaigns this year have been countered by 
increased rebel urban sabotage that is crippling angolas economy 
a second round of lowlevel peace talks ended monday in portugal 
and a portuguese official said the two sides had agreed to meet 
again probably next month however savimbi recalled his 
delegation for consultations after differences arose on the third 
day of negotiations and hardliners on both sides are still 
pressing for more military campaigns 
unita has agreed to recognize the angolan state and dos santos 
as its head while the government has indicated it might agree to 
free elections after peace neither side can agree on terms for 
monitoring a ceasefire diplomats say 
opposition to elections in the singleparty state is strong 
especially among marxist hardliners pitted against the more 
moderate dos santos 
security minister kundi payama recently told mpla militants that 
angola would maintain its marxistleninist system because 
capitalism has never served the interests of the angolan people 
billboards around the capital proclaim 1990 the year for 
broader democracy and the ruling partys third congress slated 
for december might produce steps toward multiparty democracy if a 
truce is fixed before then western observers say 
dos santos has been edging away from comunist economics since 
1987 and has brought pragmatists such as de castro van dunem into 
the politburo and his inner circle last week he promoted 
moderates in a cabinet reshuffle 
most of angolas trade and its 55 billion foreign debt is with 
the west 
the united states whose oil companies have major interests in 
angola have withheld diplomatic recognition as an incentive to get 
unita represented in government 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

