<TEXT>
eleven dominican stowaways hiding 
in the cargo hold of a puerto rican ship were killed by a pesticide 
that was sprayed on the vessels cargo of cocoa officials say 
the puerto rican government on tuesday sent condolences to the 
dominican republic over the deaths 
the 11 dominicans all of them men were discovered monday 
aboard the ss humacao owned by the puerto rico maritime shipping 
co shortly after the vessel left the southern dominican port of 
rio haina 
company officials said the cargo of the ship headed for 
elizabeth nj had been sprayed with the pesticide methyl bromide 
in compliance with us department of agriculture regulations 
the san juan star an englishlanguage daily said five of the 
men were found dead in the cargo hold and six others died later at 
a hospital from inhaling the poisonous fumes 
two stowaways in the cargo hold survived one was treated at a 
dominican hospital and released while the other was arrested on 
unspecified charges dominican authorities said 
in a letter to dominican president joaquin balaguer puerto rico 
secretary of state antonio colorado said the us commonwealth will 
work with its caribbean neighbor to avoid such tragedies in the 
future he did not specify any possible safeguards however 
in california the united farm workers union has pushed for a 
ban on the pesticide some deaths have been blamed on its use in 
fumigating homes 
dominicans fleeing the poverty of their homeland frequently stow 
away on ships bound for the united states and other foreign ports 
in 1980 22 dominican stowaways died of suffocation in the 
ballast tank of the panamanianregistered regina express bound for 
miami 
