<TEXT>
france west germany belgium the 
netherlands and luxembourg have agreed to allow people to move 
freely across their shared borders in a pact hailed as a model for 
the entire 12nation european community 
the five countries signed the agreement tuesday and it will 
include east germany after the expected reunification if the two 
germanys the required ratification by the nations parliaments may 
take two years 
the longawaited accord was in the works sinced 1985 its 
signatories agreed to end border checks have a common visa and 
asylum policy and share data on illegal aliens suspected criminals 
and missing persons 
our agreement is a model for the free movement of people 
in the european community dutch deputy foreign minister piet 
dankert told reporters on behalf of the signatory nations 
yet he doubted all 12 of the european communitys nations were 
ready to remove their borders after dec 31 1992 when the 
countries are to merge their economies to create a single 
barrierfree market 
the 12 ec states have not even reached agreement on how to 
handle asylumseekers 
negotiations are to open this week with italy which wants to 
join the schengen accord named for this village on the 
luxembourggermanfrench border where it was signed 
under the accord the five signatory nations will 
remove internal border checks for their citizens and legal 
residents and let legally admitted people from outside the five 
nations move within their boundaries for three months without a 
visa 
apply a joint policy to prevent asylum shopping whereby 
refugees go from one nation to the next to get residency visas 
intensify cooperation between police and justice officials and 
allow police to chase suspected criminals across national 
boundaries 
simplify extradition procedures and harmonize guncontrol 
legislation 
share information on people wanted or missing or who are 
considered dangerous such a databank will also keep tabs on such 
items as stolen cars and passports 
the schengen agreement primarily benefits passenger traffic on 
road transport the five ec nations pledged to keep border checks 
at the lowest possible level by removing some of the red tape 
that hampers road transporters 
the agreement allows any state to revert to fullfledged border 
checks on national security grounds 
reflecting the sensitive nature of dropping border controls 
tuesdays signing ceremony was three years behind schedule 
in past negotiations the issue has encountered several hurdles 
ranging from luxembourgs refusal to water down its bank secrecy 
laws to concerns elsewhere that the computer databank may lead to 
an invasion of privacy 
