<TEXT>
researchers have broken down a 155digit 
number into three numbers that cannot be further divided raising 
concerns about the safety of computer programs used by banks and 
the military 
scientists at bell communications research in morris township 
said tuesday they came up with three factors of the number dubbed 
the worlds most wanted number after using about 1000 
computers during a fiveweek period one of the factors is seven 
digits one 49 and the third is a 99digit number 
arjen lenstra a member of bellcores technical staff worked 
with mark manasse of digital equipment corp of palo alto calif 
to break the number down lenstra says the effort shows that 
tampering with certain computer messages encoded in 150digit 
numbers is possible 
the fact that we are able to figure this number shows that 
others are less safe than previously thought lenstra said 
but the significance of the development for major institutions 
such as banks and the military that use large numbers to encode 
computer messages was downplayed by david kahn author of the 
codebreakers 
kahn said that in most code systems both the sender and receiver 
of information have the same system and key 
in the widely used cryptographic system the research applies to 
the encoding and decoding keys differ 
the keys are related mathematically through a number that is 
usually the product of two large prime numbers the product is in 
the open but the primes are kept secret and the system depends for 
its security on the difficulty of factoring large numbers 
according to kahn 
the labs breaking down of the 155digit number indicates that 
the second system can be factored down more quickly than previously 
believed kahn said but for practical purposes the system is 
mostly used to enable one computer to recognize another 
an official with the american bankers association which 
represents about 95 percent of us commercial banks said he was 
not alarmed by the bellcore breakthrough 
most banks use the data inscription standard and i know of no 
one who has ever broken that code said al belisle chairman of 
the associations systems security committee 
</TEXT>
