the military officials who spoke on condition of anonymity had 
few details of casualties but said four rebels were killed when 
the naval base at karainagar northwest of jaffna came under rebel 
attack 
at least two soldiers were killed when rebels pounded the palali 
airfield 10 miles north of jaffna with mortars and rockets they 
said 
in their attempt today to seize the jaffna military garrison 
the rebels suffered heavy casualties the officials said 
the tigers had on tuesday launched a failed assault on the 
200yearold dutch fort where the garrison is located 
tiger rebels used armorplated bulldozers today to break down 
the doors of the fort and attempted to scale its 20foot walls the 
officials said 
bitter handtohand fighting ensued 
soldiers used helicopter gunships and armored cars to repulse 
the attack officials said 
about 1000 people are believed to have been killed since the 
tigers repudiated a yearlong ceasefire with the government on 
june 10 and overran police stations in the tamildominated north 
and east 
deputy defense minister ranjan wijeratne has said at least 600 
rebels have been killed in the fighting another 392 rebels 
soldiers policemen and civilians have also died according to 
reports compiled from tiger sources military officers and 
residents 
in the east government troops bombed and burned deserted rebel 
bunkers around the port city of batticaloa military officers said 
the rebels withdrew from the city on monday a day before 
government troops took it over 
the troops killed a tamil woman and her 10yearold child while 
advancing into the city said batticaloa residents contacted by 
telephone 
on tuesday the army made significant advances in the east 
dislodging rebels from several cities and freeing at least two army 
camps that been under seige by rebel forces as the attacks 
intensified rebels were seen fleeing the cities and towns into the 
jungle where they were expected to prepare for what could be 
another bloody guerrilla war 
the counterattacks today were seen as an attempt by the rebels 
to kick the army out of the north and allow for the establishment 
of a secure base for antigovernment operations 
the rebels took control of all major towns in the northern and 
eastern provinces after indian peackeeping troops withdrew from sri 
lanka in march the indian forces had failed to disarm the tigers 
during a 32month occupation 
government forces and tiger rebels jointly patrolled the streets 
of the towns while leaders of both sides held a series of meetings 
to decide on the political future of the regions 
the talks had not made much headway when the fighting resumed 
tamils who make up 18 percent of sri lankas 16 million people 
claim they are discriminated against by the sinhalese who make up 
75 percent of the population the sri lankan armed forces police 
and government are also dominated by the sinhalese 
before this months fighting at least 11000 people had been 
killed since tamil militants began fighting for an independent 
nation in 1983 
in 1987 india brokered a peace accord between the two sides and 
sent its peacekeeping force but the tigers reneged on the accord 
and turned their guns on the indians 
in may 1989 the government negotiated a ceasefire with the 
rebels and requested that the indians pull out 
</TEXT>
