<TEXT>
an art gallery and its director must stand 
trial in september for displaying two robert mapplethorpe 
photographs that include nude or seminude children a judge has 
ruled 
hamilton county municipal judge david albanese also said tuesday 
he plans to hear more evidence before deciding whether the 
contemporary arts center and director dennis barrie also must face 
obscenity charges for displaying five sexually graphic pictures 
i was hoping it wouldnt go to trial but now that it is going 
to trial i feel very confident we will win barrie said 
after a hearing i know that what we are doing is right and we 
will be vindicated in court 
albanese refused defense requests to dismiss the two misdemeanor 
charges against barrie and the gallery 
this court will try to make a decision of what in ohio 
constitutes the definition of obscenity the judge said 
obscene material is not protected by the first amendment this 
case is not about the rights of the curious to view an exhibition 
a county grand jury indicted the gallery and barrie on april 7 
the day the sevenweek exhibition robert mapplethorpe the 
perfect moment opened to the public if convicted barrie faces 
up to six months in jail and 1000 in fines on each charge the 
arts center faces up to 5000 in fines on each charge 
the indictments first count set for a jury trial sept 24 
charges barrie and the gallery with illegal use of a minor in 
material involving nudity the charge involves a picture of a boy 
with his genitals exposed and a picture of a girl with her genitals 
exposed 
on the second charge pandering obscenity albanese said he 
wanted to conduct an evidentiary hearing aug 20 before deciding 
whether it should go to trial 
the prosecution is asking albanese to limit the case to the 
pictures named in the indictment the defense contends the court 
must consider the 175photo exhibit as a whole including its 
portraits and pictures of flowers 
this court is not presumptuous enough to believe that it has 
the background and information necessary to try to rationalize 
whether these pictures can be taken as a whole or independently 
albanese said in ordering the aug 20 hearing 
barrie said more than 81000 people saw the exhibit before it 
closed may 26 
in his ruling albanese said he considered the contemporary arts 
center to be a gallery rather than a museum and noted that a 
museum is permitted more latitude in displaying art 
one defense request to dismiss the charges argued that ohio 
obscenity law specifically exempts material exhibited for artistic 
or educational purposes 
this court will not pretry the case in pretrial motions 
albanese said in a written copy of his ruling 
 
