<TEXT>
here are excerpts from recent editorials in newspapers in the 
united states and abroad 
june 16 
bangor maine daily news on flag burning 
the american flag which has been shot at set afire sunk with 
foundering ships vilified belittled and scorned remains a 
flawless symbol of the united states the flag remains unscathed 
not because of its material but because of the freedoms and 
responsibilities it represents by protecting the material of the 
flag through a constitutional amendment we risk weakening those 
freedoms and responsibilities 
the supreme courts 54 ruling making unconstitutional a law 
that would prohibit flag burning looked beyond the emotional 
support for the flag to the freedom for americans to express 
dissent and to challenge the government though burning the flag is 
an ugly act that many would call a type of political pornography 
this is not a question of taste but of rights 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
june 14 
the keene nh sentinel on flag burning 
thomas jefferson and james madison the principal authors of the 
bill of rights believed that the key to maintaining a free society 
was to cultivate a respect for liberty but not necessarily a 
respect for every manifestation of liberty the distinction is 
important jefferson and madison understood that the exercise of 
freedom would inevitably result in the expression of very unpopular 
opinions 
president george bush and reps chuck douglas and robert smith 
both rnh are among contemporary politicians who dont seem to 
understand that concept with unbecoming arrogance they are 
proposing to improve upon the work of jefferson and madison they 
want to pass a constitutional amendment to amend the bill of rights 
for the first time in the countrys history 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
june 14 
the plain dealer cleveland on flag burning 
the constitution protects americans right of political dissent 
even if they express their protest in ways the majority may 
deplore with its reasoned defense of the first amendments 
guarantee of free expression the supreme court should have put 
a stop to the demagoguery over an emotional nonissue the phony 
furor over flag burning 
no other nation has an absolute guarantee of its citizens 
freedoms if the right of free expression is to remain intact 
mainstream americans must tolerate dissent even in its most 
eccentric or offensive forms 
yet a momentary scare about flag burning has incited 
opportunists to cheapen the meaning of patriotism the 
moreloyalthanthou posturing stagemanaged by the white house 
in a deplorable effort to sway votes in this election year 
foreshadows another campaign season of flagfactory rallies and 
mass recitations of the pledge of allegiance 
such flag fanaticism has become worse than a mere frivolity it 
now threatens to shred the constitution itself 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
june 13 
the free press mankato minn on flag burning 
here we go again 
the supreme court again overturned a federal law prohibiting 
flag burning 
this ruling means that now were sure to see a constitutional 
amendment barreling down the congressional pike to make flag 
burning illegal lets hope sanity prevails on capitol hill and 
our representatives vote down this wrongheaded move 
few if any have ever been swayed because somebody else torched 
a flag to the contrary such acts are found by the vast majority 
of us to be repulsive 
so why not make this exception to free speech 
because the right of free speech has importance and value as one 
of the fundamental rights of our political system the first 
amendment protects unpopular speech popular speech needs no 
shield the flag has importance and value but only as a symbol of 
our system free speech is the more important right in our system 
it may be too much to hope that the demagogues of the republican 
party will let this issue drop but we can hope as we do that 
congress will reject the flag burning amendment 
</TEXT>
