<TEXT>
june 19 
the hindustan times northern india on space exploration 
president bush last month set the deadline for a manned mission 
to mars 2019 the 50th anniversary of the first apollo manned 
landing on the moon like president kennedy before him bush is 
apparently challenging the nation to spend large resources and to 
risk lives to go to another world 
nasa set up by the eisenhower administration in 1958 succeeded 
magnificently by putting 12 men onto the moon by december 1972 
can it repeat a far more complex and spectacular feat to the red 
planet in less than 29 years in fact is a manned journey to mars 
even technically feasible the red planet is hundreds of times 
farther away than the moon 
the voyage would probably take some two to two and and a half 
years to complete 50 times longer than the longest apollo mission 
and to achieve it would require technical advances on three fronts 
which are far from being accomplished 
first the effects of prolonged weightlessness have yet to be 
overcome secondly reliable closed cycle space habitats 
spaceships adequate enough for six to eight people to live and 
work in without being resupplied have to be built and thirdly a 
giant rocket with ten times more propulsion power than the saturn 
v moon rocket would be required 
since the decommissioning of saturn v the us has lacked a 
heavylift rocket the prohibitive cost estimated at an additional 
15 billion a year on top of the expense of present space 
activities doubtful technical feasibility and lack of political 
will all make the mars manned journey a dream less likely to become 
a reality 
</TEXT>
