future international aids meetings wont be 
held in the united states and other countries that restrict the 
entry of people infected with the aids virus a top conference 
official said wednesday 
its not appropriate to hold the conference in countries that 
have restrictions said dr paul volberding of the university of 
california san francisco 
volberding is the incoming president of the international aids 
society which picks the sites for the annual aids meeting he is 
also cochairman of this years gathering the sixth international 
conference on aids being held this week in san francisco 
volberding said that canada japan and australia are among other 
countries that will be barred from being hosts of the meeting 
because of similar restrictions on travel by foreigners infected 
with the aids virus 
while the united states has significantly eased rules on 
admitting people who carry hiv the aids virus the regulations 
have emerged as a major issue at this meeting and about 100 
organizations are boycotting because of them 
it isnt fair its discriminatory and it wont do anything 
to stop the spread of hiv infection volberding said 
in 1987 the us senate voted 97 to 0 to add hiv infection to 
the list of medical conditions for which foreigners can be denied 
visas in april the justice department said it would issue special 
10day visas for people traveling to the united states to attend 
specific conferences including the aids meeting without requiring 
them to admit they are infected with hiv 
administration officials have contended they cant throw out the 
hiv restriction entirely since it was imposed by the senate 
however dr june osborn chairman of the national commission on 
aids said federal health officials should regrasp their 
authority to decide which diseases are contagious enough to be on 
the list 
the 1992 aids meeting is scheduled to be sponsored by harvard 
university in boston last week harvard officials threatened to 
withdraw from the meeting unless the travel rules are changed 
on wednesday alan fein head of the harvard aids institute 
said harvard will pull out unless all restrictions on people with 
hiv infection have been eliminated by the time congress adjourns in 
november 
volberding said that if the boston meeting is abandoned it may 
be too late to find another country to be host of the 1992 
gathering the meeting is scheduled to be held in florence italy 
next year and in berlin in 1993 
the international aids meetings are the principal forum for 
exchanging new information on the spread and control of the 
epidemic an estimated 12000 scientists doctors social workers 
and other aids professionals are expected to attend this weeks 
meeting 
