<TEXT>
australia and new zealand on wednesday presented 
new evidence of increasing damage to the earths protective ozone 
layer at an international environmental conference 
scientists from the two countries have discovered a 15 percent 
drop in ozone during the last three years over macquarie island 
800 miles southeast of tasmania 
the conference attended by senior scientists and officials from 
more than 100 nations is considering a ban on ozonedepleting 
chlorofluorocarbons cfcs the conference is preparing the 
groundwork for a june 2729 meeting of environment ministers from 
56 countries 
also wednesday britains stratospheric ozone review group said 
in a separate report that the fragile ozone layer is declining in 
midlatitudes over north america and europe the report said major 
cutbacks in cfcs which are mostly used in refrigerators and 
airconditioners would slow the damage 
stratospheric chlorine is expected to continue to increase at 
levels higher than previously experienced there is a risk that 
these might trigger disproportionately larger ozone losses the 
report said 
the australian results were released to inject a sense of 
urgency back into the proceedings a conference source said 
dr mostafa tolba executive director of the united nations 
environment program appealed for international cooperation on the 
issue 
no country no region no group will ever be capable of 
solving any of these problems alone it is a must that north and 
south east and west cooperate tolba said failure is not an 
option success is imperative 
the meeting is a sequel to the 1987 montreal protocol 
conference which agreed to halve the world consumption of 
chlorofluorocarbons by the end of the century 
fiftysix countries have signed the protocol considered a 
watershed in green diplomacy it marked the first time nations 
agreed to protect the global environment against future dangers it 
also committed nations to targets before the technology was 
available to achieve them 
five months after the agreement was reached there was mounting 
scientific evidence of the threat to the ozone layer and most 
signatories said the protocol was inadequate 
if we had known in montreal what we know in london we would 
have then drawn up a much stronger treaty with much faster 
phaseout of cfcs and halons tolba said 
tolba on wednesday proposed completely eliminating cfcs and 
halon by the end of the century adding carbon tetrachloride to the 
list of ozonedepleting chemicals and cutting production and use 
of methyl chloroform by the year 2000 
chlorine gases used mainly in refrigeration systems and 
aerosols damage the ozone layer that protects life from 
ultraviolet rays a 1989 un report confirmed ozone depletion had 
started posing significant threats to food production ocean life 
and human health 
in addition to increasing the risk of skin cancers exposure to 
ultraviolet rays could cause suppression of the human immune system 
and lead to a rise in infectious diseases the report said 
cfcs also are major contributors to global warming 
but eliminating cfcs is costly for developing nations and many 
including populous china and india have not signed the protocol a 
chinese delegate said use of cfcs in his country was growing 12 
percent yearly and would cost 42 million over three years to phase 
out the chemicals 
last week the bush administration announced it was willing to 
contribute 25 million to a fund to assist developing nations to 
eliminate cfcs 
</TEXT>
