<TEXT>
the fire aboard the uss midway the navys 
oldest active aircraft carrier raises haunting questions for the 
service about its safety record and the wisdom of keeping aging 
warships at sea defense analysts said wednesday 
the 45yearold ship extensively overhauled during its career 
including a threeyear renovation from 1967 to 1970 is scheduled 
to be retired next year 
defense secretary dick cheney announced during his visit to 
japan in february that the midway whose home port is yokosuka 
would be replaced by the 31yearold uss independence like the 
midway an oilburning carrier 
the incident on the midway the last of three nearly identical 
sister ships still on active duty could hurry that schedule along 
navy sources and independent defense analysts said 
there may be an adjustment to the timetable but theyll have 
to assess the damage first said a senior navy officer who spoke 
on condition he not be mentioned by name 
joshua handler a research associate with the environmental 
advocacy group greenpeace and a critic of the navys nuclear 
weapons policies said fires aboard carriers are a particular 
concern given chances nuclear weapons are most probably aboard 
theyve had trouble with the midway for so long this may be 
the straw that breaks the camels back he said its time is 
well up and im sorry that this sort of thing had to happen to 
make the point 
after the 1970 overhaul it was discovered that so much weight 
had been added in hightech equipment that the 67000ton vessel 
rode dangerously low in the water 
sixhundredfootlong compartments were added to each side to 
increase buoyancy and and let the ship ride higher in the water 
this modifcation made the ships natural roll quicker making it 
harder to operate aircraft 
the stability of a ship is crucial when the ships f14 jet 
fighters or a6e attack planes slam onto its deck traveling at more 
than 100 mph 
navy spokesman cmdr jim mitchell said the midway fire 
apparently was confined to a rather small area in compartments 
that store firefighting and emergency repair equipment 
all sailors on board ship are trained to fight fires at special 
schools in norfolk va and san diego calif to help deal with 
such emergencies he said 
we train our people in damage control its not because we 
expect problems but these things do happen given the hazardous 
nature of a ships operations at sea you cant call for the fire 
department every sailor is the fire department he said 
the navys safety record has come under intense scrutiny in the 
wake of last years explosion aboard the uss iowa in which 47 
sailors lost their lives 
following a sixweek string of mishaps last fall the navy 
ordered all ships and planes to undergo a 48hour standdown to 
review safety procedures 
the service maintains that its safety record has improved over 
the past decade with its best safety records compiled in 1988 and 
1989 
five years ago there were 101 major accidents involving surface 
ships aircraft and submarines in 1989 there were 69 and in 1990 
so far there have been 23 the navy said 
in calender 1989 the service recorded 104 deaths in training 
and operations a number which includes the iowa 47 so far this 
year nine fatalities have occurred the navy said 
during the reagan administration the navy once had plans for a 
600ship navy and it did grow to 585 it has 15 carrier battle 
groups fourteen groups are deployed at any one time with one 
carrier always in overhaul 
now a much smaller navy is in store amid the lessening soviet 
threat and budget pressures one day before the midway fire broke 
out cheney revealed that a possible 25 percent cut in the nations 
force structure would reduce the navy to 455 warships and an even 
dozen deployed carrier groups 
some on capitol hill have pressed for even deeper cuts in the 
carrier fleet 
the influential chairman of the senate armed services committee 
sen sam nunn dga has recommended as few as 10 
you hurt people by keeping men on these things contended 
david isenberg an analyst with the center for defense information 
who wrote a critical study of carrier battle groups for the 
independent research group the cato institute which generally 
advocates conservative positions 
isenberg argues that building new carriers at 33 billion each 
plus associated costs for planes and escorts is not the most 
efficient use of the navys funds in the postcold war era 
carriers have rendered enormous service to the nation and 
still have a role to perform he said but he argues that the 
navy should make more use of attack submarines in order to 
achieve a mix of capabilities in which less emphasis is place on 
power projection and more on sea control 
