the number of passengers taking domestic us 
flights has leveled off over the last three years after years of 
increasing travel an industry report said wednesday 
the report however predicted huge growth in air travel by the 
end of the century 
passengers flying within the united states increased only 1 
percent in 1989 while the number of passengers boarding 
international flights from us airports rose 11 percent the 
airport operators council international said 
our traffic results for 1989 might indicate a slight weakening 
in the growth rate of aviation for the year but we foresee a 61 
percent increase in passenger traffic by 2000 said george 
howard aoci president 
an accompanying report by the partnership for improved air 
travel said aviations contribution to the economy hit nearly 600 
billion in 1989 a 138 percent increase over the last study which 
covered 1987 the most dramatic growth was in commercial aircraft 
manufacturing where jobs payrolls and other economic factors rose 
22 percent 
aviations share of the gross national product remained at 56 
percent said the partnership a wideranging group set up to 
ensure that us aviation meets future demands 
reports by the two aviation organizations were released at a 
joint news conference 
howard blamed slow overall economic growth higher fares and the 
eastern airlines strike for the stalled growth in domestic 
passengers he said tight capacity at larger airports also may be 
hindering growth in traffic 
the aocis annual traffic report on each of the worlds major 
