<TEXT>
oncesecret radiation exposure records for 
200000 nuclear weapons plant workers will soon be released to a 
group that monitors power plant safety a lawyer said wednesday 
the records will be analyzed to determine the health effects of 
lowlevel exposure to radiation said daniel berger attorney for 
the three mile island public health fund the organization 
represents people who live near the nuclear power plant that was 
the site of nations worst commercial nuclear accident 
lawyers for the us energy department agreed a month ago to 
turn over the information but berger said some paperwork remains 
to be worked out 
there has never been access to this data other than by 
researchers in the department of energy berger said its been 
tightly controlled 
the data which is on computer tapes will be analyzed by 
researchers at birmingham university in england alice stewart who 
heads the the research team took part in a project more than a 
decade ago that found a startlingly high incidence of cancer among 
workers at the hanford nuclear reservation in washington state 
if the preliminary findings at hanford are borne out it seems 
to me the occupational safety standards will have to be heightened 
at nuclear facilities said berger 
the first records are expected for 50000 hanford workers the 
government has also agreed to turn over records for 90000 workers 
at four more plants the savannah river site in south carolina the 
linde plant in tonawanda ny and the x10 and y12 plants at the 
oak ridge reservation in tennessee 
the records include details about the sex and race of the 
workers and their age when they were exposed to radiation the 
doses they received and their job titles and occupational 
histories 
if the workers have died the records also list the cause and 
date of death to protect the workers privacy their names are to 
be withheld 
as soon as possible the government has promised to turn over 
similar records for 60000 workers from these plants rocky flats 
colo los alamos national laboratory nm mound laboratory 
miamisburg ohio and the pantex facility amarillo texas 
by may 18 1991 the energy department has pledged to turn over 
records for 20000 workers at the k25 plant at oak ridge the 
mallinckrodt chemical works in st louis and the feed material 
production center in fernald ohio 
stewart the birmingham researcher told the philadelphia 
inquirer she expects the new data to show three to five times as 
many cancer cases as most experts expect to find among people who 
have been exposed to lowlevel radiation 
the hanford study she worked on in the late 1970s found 
unusually high rates of pancreatic lung and bonemarrow cancer 
among workers even those exposed to radiation levels 30 times 
lower than the government safety minimum 
the government discontinued funding for the study and turned 
aside legal efforts to give the data to the researchers or others 
on grounds it was protecting the workers privacy 
the tmi public health fund pursued the data as a source of 
information about longterm exposure to lowlevel radiation berger 
said the energy department agreed last year to release the records 
the fund will be first to get the records but they also will be 
available to other researchers with the capacity to use the 
computer tapes said jeff sherwood an energy department spokesman 
the fund was set up in 1981 as part of a settlement of a lawsuit 
brought by people living within 25 miles of the three mile island 
nuclear power plant against the plant and its owners operators and 
insurers 
