<TEXT>
charles p farnsley a colorful 
politician who for a time adopted southern planters garb and who 
as louisville mayor invited ordinary people to air their gripes at 
city hall has died he was 83 
the democrat who died tuesday at a nursing home here was mayor 
from 1948 to 1953 and served in the us house of representatives 
from 1965 to 1967 he was a state legislator for four years in the 
1930s 
officials at the nursing home and funeral home wednesday evening 
were unable to give a cause of death 
as mayor farnsley may have been best known for the beef 
session every monday night he held court at city hall inviting 
any citizen with a problem or complaint to present it directly to 
him 
he energetically attacked what he saw as the citys problems 
farnsley turned empty lots into parks installed street lights 
raised city workers salaries improved police and firefighters 
pensions converted old schools into community centers and replaced 
old garbage trucks 
charlie was really one of the great planners and builders of 
the city said frank burke sr a lawyer who was mayor from 1969 
to 1973 
but he may be better remembered for his eccentricities 
farnsley was a history buff who went through a confederate 
period in the 1930s when his normal dress was a broad planters 
hat a swallowtailed coat a brocade vest and a black string tie 
he published books under the lost cause press label and bottled 
whimsically named brands of whiskey like rebel yell he tried 
to name another brand damyankee but it was rejected by the 
copyright office as being in bad taste he submitted a new brand 
name bad taste 
he abandoned confederate garb in later years except for the 
string tie which became his trademark but he frequently carried a 
carpetbag when he traveled to northern cities 
television came to louisville during his stint as mayor and he 
bought sets for the public libraries since few people had them at 
home 
people might as well look in a library as in a bar it makes 
business for the bar why cant it make business for the library 
he asked 
book circulation reportedly skyrocketed 
farnsley is survived by daughters sally bird of arlington va 
and ann farnsley of vevay ind sons alexander of la jolla 
calif and burrel and douglass both of louisville and six 
grandchildren 
services were scheduled for thursday in louisville 
