<TEXT>
the exotic agra diamond once worn in a 16th 
century mogul emperors turban became the most expensive pink 
diamond in the world wednesday when it was auctioned for a record 
695 million 
the 3224 carat agra the largest pink diamond ever auctioned 
was sold to siba rare jewels of hong kong after heated bidding at 
christies showroom in london siba made their successful bid by 
telephone 
the sale of the agra diamond easily eclipsed the previous record 
sale price for a pink diamond of 61 million set in may 1989 
raymond sancroftbaker senior director of christies jewelry 
department said i am delighted i had expected it to fetch 42 
million to 47 million its history obviously pushed up the 
price 
the agra the worlds seventh largest pink diamond was mined in 
the golconda region of indias hyderabad province 
it was seized by babur the founder of the mogul dynasty in 
1526 when he conquered india and took the gem after defeating the 
rajah of gwalior 
along with the agra babur also took the kohinoor diamond now 
one of the principle treasures in britains crown jewels he gave 
the kohinoor to his son humayun but kept the agra for himself 
wearing it in his turban 
the cushionshaped agra was the centerpiece of a jewelry auction 
that brought in 22 million and broke a previous record of 94 
million set at christies in june 1989 
other highlights of the sale included the 1849 carat golden 
drop a pearshaped yellow diamond bought by londons graff 
jewelers for 367 million a record for a yellow diamond 
like the agra the stones came from the winans collection and 
were offered for sale by a descendant of american collector louis 
winans 
the agra has also belonged to britains duke of brunswick the 
eccentric 19th century collector who bought it in 1944 
it weighed 4175 carats at that time but was cut down to its 
present weight in the late 19th century to eliminate imperfections 
it was later bought by bram hertz of paris who sold it in 1891 
to the london jeweler edwin streeter in 1905 the diamond was 
included in a sale at christies and was bought by max meyer 
in 1910 winans bought the gem with money inherited from his 
father engineer william winans who built the railway that ran 
from moscow to st petersburg in the mid19th century the stone 
was inherited by the current owner 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

