<TEXT>
when highly successful business people suddenly 
lose their magic touch often at what seems the apex of their 
careers you may find vanity plays a role in the drama 
vanity combined with financial leverage and economic cyclicality 
often drive their success the trio are the heroes of the ascent 
ironically they are also the villains of the decline 
you can find them at work in stocks bonds and commodities in 
las vegas and atlantic city in real estate merchandising 
banking politics they are eager supporters in the ascent savage 
enemies in the fall 
you can find two or all three in the major downfalls of business 
history in the savings and loan collapses in the bankruptcy of 
the hunt brothers who thought they could corner the silver market 
in ivan boesky the investor 
they are current in the affairs of william farley who tried to 
expand his textile empire before he had the money to pay for it 
and of robert campeau who became one of the worlds biggest 
retailers and then lost it all 
the three bad actors are especially prominent in building and 
real estate and are on stage in most real estate collapses they 
are visible and vocal in the affairs of several real estate gurus 
who rose from nothing and returned to it 
decades ago they helped bring down william zeckendorf one of 
the most famous real estate men of his time the man who assembled 
the land on which the united nations stands and today they are 
involved in donald trumps problems 
the scenario is deadly clear whether it evolves on the smallest 
of stages or the largest an example 
in the 1970s inflation raged those who kept savings in the 
bank saw them wither because interest rates earned were in the 
single digits while the buying power of money shrank at double 
digit rates 
while inflation shriveled the value of money it caused the 
prices of hard assets to soar the value of money in the bank 
deteriorated the value of money in real estate soared savvy 
people flocked to real estate 
bankers took notice not only did they lend money to building 
developers but they took a piece of the action themselves bankers 
sought out the more daring dramatic and successful developers and 
shoveled money at them 
inflation continued developers succeeded lenders lent how 
could you lose some developers believed they couldnt and some of 
the lenders tended to agree with them the borrowers borrowed more 
the lenders lent them more 
leverage became the name of the game the squeamish warned that 
it was dangerous to borrow so freely especially with interest 
rates rising but the daring ones were convinced they had mastered 
the magic formula 
then the economy began cooling and as it cooled the inflation 
rates began falling the jobless rate began rising people couldnt 
buy houses and apartments and they couldnt afford the high rents 
the game was over 
as the economy came plunging down into the recession of the 
early 1980s it toppled those who felt they could do not wrong who 
leveraged themselves who allowed their vanity to violate their own 
good judgment 
looking back almost every one of those involved in that debacle 
knew that the laws of good banking the principles of business and 
the economic cycle had not been revoked but they chose not to 
think about it 
instead their successes inflated their confidence and their 
confidence allowed them to borrow beyond reason in their clouded 
minds they knew it had to end someday but they chose instead to be 
guided by their vanity 
hadnt that vanity given them the courage to build empires why 
then should they not rely on it just once more just one more 
time they said while they sought to put a crown on their 
achievements 
</TEXT>
