after one year the marriage between boston university and 
chelseas schools is a little rocky 
the idea was to give the private university control of this 
failing school district with its high dropout rates low grades 
and even lower budgets bu would get the prestige of operating this 
unique and highprofile laboratory chelsea would benefit from bus 
educational and financial resources 
but after year one of the 10year program the universitys goal 
of stirring chelseas children as the public system could not 
is a long way off 
money still is short it took more than eight tense months for 
the teachers union to settle a contract with bu the experiment is 
being contested in the courts good intentions also have been 
tangled in the knot of advisory and oversight committees and in 
the conflicting interests of the aldermen school committee 
hispanic community groups and parents 
the biggest thing is getting through the mine fields of the 
state in financial chaos the city in chaos and all the petty 
bickering said peter greer bus dean of education and overseer 
of the management project 
bu installed diane lam as superintendent to engineer the 10year 
experiment and she uses the marriage metaphor 
hopefully it will be a love marriage that can develop 
trust she told the governors committee appointed to watch over 
the unusual relationship or it can be dissolved 
bu wants to remake the schools and attitudes about education 
in this workingclass city of 26000 people many from latin 
american and asia nearly onethird of the systems 3500 students 
come from families in which english is not the first language 
some programs were established this year notably alternative 
courses for kids with failing grades and afterschool programs in 
the elementary grades 
though 16yearold amy sandelin endured a sometimes tumultuous 
year under the new system shes eager for her senior year when 
she will be in the new renaissance school which will allow her to 
study what interests her most 
the arrival of bu sandelin said with a smile is really a 
good opportunity to do something with this school for a long time 
kids with potential they lost them now a lot of kids feel theres 
more opportunity 
other programs are being tried on a small scale limited only by 
a lack of money a literacy program for example teaches english 
to two generations at once by having parents read to their children 
bus aim to boost teachers low salaries and professional 
opportunities was a hardfought effort that seemed to take forever 
to resolve 
on june 13 the second to last day of school the teachers union 
finally accepted a contract that will increase their pay anywhere 
from 24 percent to 28 percent over three years the top salary for 
teachers with bachelors degrees is now 27813 with merit 
increases it will go up to 35620 
the contract also includes an advancement program for teachers 
who are not interested in the administrative route 
but the boldest most expensive part of bus plan to provide 
health nutrition and dental care for children from birth has 
gone nowhere 
greer blames bad times in massachusetts for a lack of money and 
commitment from big foundations efforts to raise 3 million have 
netted just 18 million in gifts and pledges the biggest chunk 
for computers and software 
the city now is being asked to give the schools a 19 million 
increase for the next school year over this years 12 million 
budget mostly for salaries and special education expenses that bu 
donations are not allowed to pay 
but money wont quell uncertainties among chelsea residents and 
among some teachers who feel the changes have come too fast 
as lorraine ruby an art teacher at chelsea for 27 years put it 
we know bu can really do good things here we want to make sure 
its substantive were not a media event were real lives here 
lam said much of this unease can be traced to the fact that 
its a new type of partnership so we have not had a road map of 
which direction to take change is always hard and it makes people 
anxious 
fiftyone chelsea residents and the chelsea teachers union have 
asked the state supreme court to declare the arrangement 
unconstitutional they say members of the chelsea school committee 
have lost their voices in school policy since the university began 
managing the school system a year ago 
in all other cities and towns the parents voters and school 
committees decide questions such as who will be superintendent or 
the high school principal said juan vega a plaintiff in 
chelsea top educators are terminated in secret no public 
discussion is allowed no reasons given this is disrespectful to 
the people of chelsea 
harold raynolds state commissioner of education once 
criticized the arrangement on those grounds the school committee 
he said had abdicated its elected duty to a bu management team 
but he notes happily that the school committee and the managers now 
meet monthly for a more cooperative effort 
it is a major success that they are still there after a year 
in operation said tom shannon executive director of the national 
association of school boards in alexandria va 
to look for results in the first year is asking too much 
said shannon whose organization represents the nations 15350 
school districts and is closely watching the chelsea project 
what chelsea will exemplify is what educators have known all 
the time the growing season of education is a long long time 
dont look at your watch look at your calendar 
