<TEXT>
there is no mystery to the especially sharp 
decline in building activity the explanation is right there in the 
numbers on the record in the pattern of past economic cycles 
all of those indicate that the building business in its many 
variations has a long history of anticipating ups and downs of the 
economic cycle and of reacting more sharply than others to changes 
illustration when the economy in general weakens as now the 
situation already is an old story to homebuilders their downturn 
began months earlier and as in the past the impact on them is 
deeper than on other industries 
may housing starts fell to their lowest since the 1982 
recession dropping to an annual rate of 1207 million units a 
level reached after percentage declines of 14 in may 64 in april 
and 122 in march 
why should housing construction get the worst of downturns 
simply because it often gets the best of upturns when economic 
times get better they often get very much better in housing and 
when they get bad they get very bad 
conditions are poor now for many reasons but playing a 
prominent role is the inability of builders to obtain financing 
again as in the past when lenders become reluctant lenders they 
become especially so with builders 
the reason lies in the nature of building which is 
entrepreneurial and speculative the smallest and largest builders 
borrow heavily to begin their projects and all have the same grand 
hopes of immediate sale on completion 
too often lenders have seen builders produce a glut of product 
at the very time the economy is beginning to tip into a new down 
cycle too often they have been unable to collect their loans too 
often they have seen bankruptcies 
reflecting unique conditions loan officers are especially wary 
of making bad loans these days with regulators and their own 
boards looking over their shoulders high on their list of nonos 
therefore are builders 
while housing and real estate people have long complained about 
exaggerated impacts of economic policy which periodically pushes 
them into depression they are especially upset now 
two headlines in realtor news a weekly publication suggest the 
mood the first is unwarranted credit crunch unfairly hurting 
real estate the second theres money but will they lend 
it 
in a survey of 1142 members of the national association of home 
builders 60 percent said a credit crunch exists and that it is 
hurting them in spite of denials by bank regulators that a credit 
crackdown has been imposed 
whatever the cause the homebuilding industry once again has 
preceded other industries into recession and once again the depth 
of the decline in housing is deeper than elsewhere 
and because homebuilding has declined so much you might say the 
conditions are being produced that will lead to the next 
exaggerated cycle 
it goes like this because not enough houses were built during 
the downturn a shortage looms because of the downturn and because 
after all loans are what make profits for a bank lenders begin 
looking around for customers 
homebuilding leads the economic cycle whether up or down 
anticipating that the cycle will turn up builders rush to get 
their products on the market lenders are eager to help 
eventually another glut develops 
remember this when it does sometime in the future know that 
the rest of the economy soon will be headed down 
