<TEXT>
a slump in us oil prices to twoyear lows has surprised 
analysts by its severity but they contend the weakness is only a 
shortterm blip and wont lead to much lower gasoline prices 
tuesdays close at 1565 for a 42gallon barrel of west texas 
intermediate crude oil is much lower than i thought it would 
go said maureen allyn chief economist at scudder stevens amp 
clark inc in new york 
but ms allyn and other analysts dont see a repeat of the oil 
market crash of the mid 1980s which saw prices drop below 10 a 
barrel most analysts are sticking with forecasts that predict the 
price of wti the benchmark us grade will average around 18 a 
barrel this year 
wti for july delivery lost 29 cents in tuesdays trading on the 
new york mercantile exchange and has fallen 193 in the last week 
the price hit a fouryear high at 2368 on jan 3 but has lost 
ground pretty steadily because of heavy production by the 
organization of petroleum exporting countries 
the posted price what refiners will pay for oil on the spot 
market has fallen from as high as 21 a barrel in early january to 
as low as 15 
we would have thought that it would not have fallen as far as 
it did said david lee smith energy analyst at eppler guerin 
and turner inc in dallas because of the slippage smith has 
dropped his estimate for the 1990 average price from about 19 a 
barrel to 18 
kent hance chairman of the energy industryregulating texas 
railroad commission predicted the price will slip to 15 a barrel 
by next months scheduled opec meeting 
thats not all bad news for us said hance opec does not 
do a good job in their meetings unless their backs are up against 
the wall 
i still stay by my prediction of 24 to 25abarrel oil 
within the next 24 months he said 
the cartel has said it wants world oil prices around 18 a 
barrel but members have flouted their own production limits 
designed to keep prices firm 
last week opec president sadek boussena warned that oil prices 
would collapse unless cartel members adhered to a may agreement 
limiting production to between 221 million and 226 million 
barrels of oil a day 
estimates of opec production generally range above 23 million 
barrels daily with several group members believed to be exceeding 
their quotas 
production also has been strong among some nonopec countries 
such as norway which announced over the weekend it would increase 
its output 
that will add production to the worldwide supply but were 
seeing lower production from the united states lower production 
from the soviet union so i think that the slide in oil prices is a 
shortterm event said john hilton analyst for argus research in 
new york 
hilton said he is holding by his prediction of 1850 for this 
years average but continued deterioration could change that 
outlook 
ms allyn said there is little to indicate a longterm price 
decline failure to invest in finding new reserves during the last 
decade when oil prices were weak means declining supply and 
rising prices she said 
in terms of the real things that will drive oil prices over 
the next three to five years as a consumer i would feel no sense 
of security she said 
you cant bring new stuff on properly at these prices theres 
no incentive 
while the price has fallen much lower than she expected ms 
allyn said she did not anticipate the slump would last long enough 
to change her forecast of a 1990 average price of about 18 
reaching about 20 next year 
