motorola has earned a temporary reprieve allowing 
it to continue selling its popular computer chip but analysts say 
continuing legal battles over patent rights could shake customers 
confidence 
the us court of appeals for the federal circuit on tuesday 
granted the company a temporary stay of a federal judges ruling 
that would have forced it to pull the chip from the market 
motorola spokesman tim kellogg said the court is a special appeals 
court for patents in washington 
earlier tuesday us district judge lucius bunton had banned 
the production and sale of motorolas mc68030 microprocessor and 
hitachi ltds h8532 microprocessor 
the two companies once partners have been embroiled in a 
longstanding patent infringement battle over the microprocessor 
the device that performs computations in a computer 
some analysts said buntons decision would pose greater problems 
for motorola its chip has sold better than hitachis in this 
country garnering 17 percent of the market for 32bit 
microprocessors according to one analysts estimate 
its certainly going to shake the confidence of companies that 
have been designing with motorolas microprocessor all along 
said alice leeper associate director for dataquest a market 
research company based in san jose calif 
people who were considering doing a design based around the 
030 would certainly be thinking twice and possibly looking at an 
alternative product said ms leeper 
