<TEXT>
opec president sadek boussena is 
expected in saudi arabia sunday for consultations on overproduction 
by cartel member states amid fears of an oil price crash official 
sources said wednesday 
the sources who spoke on condition they not be identified said 
that boussena will be arriving in the saudi summer capital of 
jiddah from iran as part of a tour of opec member states to seek 
action to help stabilize erratic oil prices 
ministers of the 13nation organization of petroleum exporting 
countries agreed in may to slash opec output by 14 million barrels 
per day to restore the cartels overall production to 22 million 
barrels in support of the 18abarrel reference price 
saudi arabia the dominant party in the cartel and also one of 
the member states that had been overproducing has cut back its 
excess output but other violators have not done so and oil prices 
have been sagging they are presently fluctuating in the range of 
15 a barrel 
boussena recently warned of an oil price crash if all opec 
members did not adhere to their individual production quotas the 
saudi monarch king fahd has also urged other opec members to 
adhere to their quotas in the interest of all 
a stream of editorials in the progovernment saudi media have 
since been lashing out at the production cheaters with the latest 
in the leading alriyadh warning that the resulting flooding of 
the market is creating chaos and an imbalance that will lead to 
a price crash 
none of the overproducers have been named by either the king or 
the papers united arab emirates oil minister mana saeed otaiba on 
a recent visit to the kingdom has been pledging commitment but the 
uae on principle insists on producing at a selfimposed quota 
almost double the 1095 million barrel per day which opec has 
prescribed for it 
fahd has also said in a recent press interview that he saw the 
time ripe for a longterm agreement that would ensure a high 
degree of stability for opec and the world economy 
the saudi kings statements have been followed by renewed talk 
in some opec capitals particularly kuwait of the 2yearold 
proposal by venezuelan president carlos andres perez for an opec 
summit to discuss a fresh longterm policy for the cartel amid a 
developing upsurge in world demand for opec oil 
the sources said the oil ministers of saudi arabia kuwait 
united arab emirates qatar oman and bahrain members of the 
sixnation gulf cooperation council alliance will be meeting in 
jiddah next week to discuss various developments related to the oil 
situation 
the meeting would be held once boussena had completed his trip 
through the gulf region the sources said 
