<DOCNO> AP900620-0233 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
bills that would crack down on penny stock 
fraud and increase the authority of the securities and exchange 
commission to seek fines and halt alleged wrongdoing cleared a 
house panel wednesday 
the penny stock reform act and the securities law enforcement 
remedies act passed a subcommittee of the house energy and commerce 
committee by voice vote and now are subject to consideration by the 
full committee 
the remedies act would give the sec the power to issue cease 
and desist orders against suspected wrongdoers without having to 
go to court first 
unlike many other federal regulatory agencies like the federal 
trade commission the sec does not have the authority to halt 
alleged illegal activity without a court order 
the penny stock bill would give the sec power to bar crooked 
promoters and consultants from selling highly speculative stocks 
which usually sell for a dollar or less 
penny stocks lowpriced and often risky securities are traded 
over the counter rather than on a stock exchange because most 
information about them comes from the brokers who sell them 
investments in penny stocks which typically are used to finance 
new or small companies are considered chancey at best 
penny stocks are not in themselves illegal but a 1989 study by 
the north american securities administrators association a 
washingtonbased organization of state investment regulators 
claimed that american investors lost about 2 billion a year in 
penny stock scams 
for most of the last decade the unscrupulous brokers and 
promoters in the penny stock market have preyed on unsuspecting 
investors in a cloudy atmosphere of regulatory neglect and public 
ignorance said rep edward j markey chairman of the finance 
and telecommunications subcommittee markey introduced the bill in 
april with the subcommittees ranking republican matthew j 
rinaldo of new jersey 
the version passed by the subcommittee differed from the 
original bill however which would have required all penny stocks 
to be listed on an automated stock price quotation system the 
amended version only requires the sec to facilitate at the 
earliest feasible time an automated quote system 
the new version also watered down original restrictions on 
socalled blank check investments which seek customers money 
without a specific business plan or purpose and blind pool 
penny stocks which seek mergers and acquisitions in a specific 
industry or line of business 
rather than an outright ban the amended version would require 
the sec to adopt rules calling for improved disclosure of 
information about companies selling penny stocks to the public 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

