<TEXT>
motorola inc plans to establish the 
first global satellitebased cellular phone system at a cost of up 
to 2 billion according to a report published wednesday 
the system would require the launching of a network of 
loworbiting satellites that would extend cellular services into 
remote areas of the united states and around the world the chicago 
tribune reported 
the system would be used by international travelers and 
residents of remote areas of the united states where it would not 
be economical to build landbased transmitters of cellular signals 
analysts said the systems cost could total 1 billion to 2 
billion 
telephone calls to motorola officials seeking comment were not 
returned wednesday motorola officials have scheduled a briefing on 
tuesday in new york to unveil the system 
industry sources say it would involve launching about 70 small 
satellites to carry telephone signals around the world and would 
be operating by the mid1990s approval by the federal 
communications commission would be required 
john pemberton an analyst with gartner group inc a research 
firm in stamford conn said the system would represent a major 
change in cellular communications technology 
pemberton said he believes motorola is planning a system that 
will use a groundbased and satellite system 
he said as the user moves from an area covered by the ground 
system to a more remote area the satellite system would take over 
without the user noticing any change in voice or data transmission 
quality 
the tribune reported that motorola is finalizing agreements with 
a number of companies capable of launching its satellites among 
them washington dcbased orbital sciences corp 
the company uses its pegasus rocket to launch small playloads 
into orbit from airplanes 
with the satellite system motorola would move into an area 
currently dominated by telephone companies 
pemberton said american telephone amp telegraph co is one company 
in particular that could be hurt by motorolas move 
he said motorola moved up an announcement of its plans for a 
satellite system from later this year to get a jump on competitors 
and to have it established as the standard for the industry 
reportedly other communications companies also are moving into 
global cellular telephone technology 
atampt reportedly has teamed up with washingtonbased geostar 
corp to develop a system similar to the one being planned by 
motorola 
the fcc already has licensed american mobile satellite corp to 
launch and operate a mobile communications system for the united 
states said ruth pritchardkelly a company spokeswoman 
officials of american mobile say the company has plans to launch 
its first satellite a geostationary unit in 1993 to provide voice 
and data communications to mobile telephone users in this country 
schaumburg illbased motorola is the worlds biggest supplier 
of cellular phone systems and mobile and portable phones 
pemberton said the companys system would stimulate sales of 
motorola cellular telephone equipment 
