<TEXT>
a getty petroleum corp subsidiary and one of 
its executives were accused wednesday of conspiring with two 
customers to evade payment on 946000 in federal gasoline excise 
taxes 
getty terminals corp which distributes gasoline in the 
northeast and one of its managers william rea were named in the 
fourcount indictment returned by a federal grand jury in new york 
the justice department said the indictment was part of a 
continuing investigation into what officials called the evasion of 
an estimated 1 billion a year in federal fuel excise taxes by 
gasoline wholesalers 
the indictment charged that getty terminals and rea then the 
supply and trading manager conspired with the owners of two new 
york city gasoline wholesale distributorships to evade payment of 
the excise taxes 
john pabone owner of j amp j petroleum inc and john quock 
owner of tun yung oil corp were also accused in the indictment of 
participating in the scheme the two wholesalers are accused of 
agreeing to share in the proceeds of the unpaid taxes 
getty terminals and rea now a getty vice president were 
accused of filing false invoices to disguise the sales of 104 
million gallons of gasoline as taxfree transactions to evade 
payment of 946000 in excise gases 
tun yung had registered with the internal revenue service as a 
producer and was therefore eligible to purchase gasoline from getty 
terminals without paying excise taxes 
but getty and tun yung were required to pay excise taxes of 9 
cents for each gallon of gasoline sold to jampj according to the 
indictment 
the indictment charged that getty terminals had agreed to 
disguise sales to jampj as taxfree sales to tun yung 
getty terminals said in a statement that it collected and 
remitted all taxes it was required to collect 
getty terminals has absolutely no motive to refrain from 
collecting taxes inasmuch as all taxes collected are remitted to 
the irs in fact getty pays in excess of 200 million in taxes 
each year the statement said 
the company also defended rea saying it has the highest 
regard for his integrity honesty and competence the statement 
said he had volunteered for and passed a lie detector test 
if convicted getty terminals could be fined up to 2 million 
each of the three individuals could be sentenced to up to 20 years 
in prison and fined 1 million if convicted 
in a separate indictment returned by the same grand jury two 
brothers who own wholesale fuel companies in westchester county 
ny were charged with participating in a complicated scheme to 
purchase untaxed gasoline 
