from carrying calls to or from the united states 
ameritech and bell atlantic said they were asking us district 
judge harold greene who oversaw the bell system breakup for a 
waiver from the consent decree provisions 
if greene does not grant their request the companies would have 
to form another company to carry the international traffic said 
hyde tucker president and chief executive officer of bell atlantic 
international 
he said it would cost millions to perform such a 
reorganization 
thomas p hester ameritech vice president and general counsel 
said he believed greene would grant the waiver 
similar relief was previously granted by the court to pacific 
telesis another of the bell companies subject to the decree when 
pacific purchased an interest in a foreign overseas cable 
venture hester said in a statement 
tucker said the ameritechbell atlantic request was less 
problematic because the new zealand company handles traffic jointly 
with us carriers and wont be competing with us companies 
us carriers compete among themselves at the us end and the 
new zealand telephone company does not seek authority to enter that 
competition tucker said it only asks authority to continue to 
carry its own end of the calls 
ameritech and bell atlantic announced june 14 that they and two 
new zealand companies fay richwhite holdings ltd and freightways 
holdings ltd will purchase new zealands stateowned phone 
system under the plan the two american companies will reduce 
their combined stake to 499 percent eventually but will remain as 
controlling shareholders 
</TEXT>
