<TEXT>
the slump in the defense industry hit the 
pentagons two biggest contractors again wednesday with mcdonnell 
douglas corp announcing plans for major layoffs and general 
dynamics corp getting its credit rating cut 
mcdonnell douglas the nations biggest defense contractor 
announced plans to eliminate at least 700 million a year from its 
cost structure including laying off a substantial number of 
its 127000 workers worldwide 
the hard reality is that we must begin immediately to take 
further strong actions to reduce our costs said john f 
mcdonnell chairman and chief executive 
mcdonnell said the costcutting plan should be in place by early 
august with immediate steps being taken on overtime travel new 
hiring consultants advertising and support activities 
we have done a lot to downsize the defense cutbacks including 
bringing aerospace work to st louis from long beach said 
company spokesman jim reed despite that were going to have to 
reduce our size to improve profitability 
officals declined to reveal the number of planned layoffs which 
will be made within the next few months st louis television 
stations quoted unnamed company sources as saying the cuts could be 
up to 10 percent of mcdonnell douglas workforce 
also on wednesday moodys investor services inc dropped its 
credit ratings two notches for general dynamics nations second 
biggest defense contractor 
both companies are headquartered in st louis 
moodys dropped general dynamics senior bonds from a2 to baa1 
and the companys subordinated debt from a3 to baa2 because of the 
sagging conditions in the defense industry 
the ratings put the companys bonds into the bottom category of 
investment grade issues 
general dynamics makes f16 fighter jets for the air force m1 
tanks for the army and ssn688 submarines for the navy it also 
owns cessna aircraft co and makes a launch rocket used to put 
satellites into orbit 
moodys said it believes that the manufacturers of defense 
platforms planes tanks submarines will be the most severely 
affected by reduced defense spending 
defense secretary dick cheney is proposing a 25 percent cut in 
the nations military spending wich would retire six active duty 
army divisions 111 navy ships and 11 air force tactical fighter 
wings 
fred pastore associate director of the high technology group at 
moodys said another reason for the credit rating downgrade was 
the companys decreased amount of readily available cash 
general dynamics spokesman pete connolly said the company was 
disappointed with the downgrade but he said we feel we have 
both a strong balance sheet and a strong balance of business which 
will sustain us through this period 
in new york industry analyst paul nisbet of prudentialbache 
said the mcdonnell douglas layoffs should not be regarded as a sign 
the company which has a hefty backlog of commercial aircraft 
orders is in trouble 
it would stand to reason with the likelihood of somewhat lower 
activity on several of their military programs said nisbet 
the companys probably going to have a 20 percent increase in 
sales next year primarily because of increase in commercial 
aircraft 
mcdonnell douglas which has 10 plants in the united states 
reported sales of 1458 billion last year compared with 144 
billion in 1988 
were projecting them at 162 billion this year over 18 
billion in 1991 and to 20 billion by 1992 nisbet said 
theyve got a wealth of business with over 50 billion in 
backlog 
the layoffs represent just a shift in business from what 
predominantly was a military market in the 80s to a predominantly 
commercial market in the 90s nisbet said theyre just having 
trouble digesting it 
douglas aircraft in long beach its production behind schedule 
on the c17 cargo plane has lost 306 million the past 15 months 
to trim its costs the company has begun cutting 7000 jobs mostly 
white collar at its plants in long beach and nearby torrance 
calif 
mcdonnell douglas programs that would be affected by cheneys 
proposed cuts include the harpoon and tomahawk missiles and the 
f15 and fa18 jet fighters employees were informed of layoffs on 
wednesday by closedcircuit television 
