<TEXT>
a delaware court has ruled that the royal 
dutchshell group violated disclosure rules in its 57 billion 
buyout of minority shareholders in the former shell oil co five 
years ago 
the court of chancery in new castle county delaware ruled in 
favor of a group of minority shareholders who had sued over the 
terms of the buyout 
tuesdays ruling did not determine how much the former owners of 
15 million shares of shell stock should be awarded said houston 
attorney ken mcneil who represented the plaintiffs 
the judge asked both sides to submit recommendations on the 
award but did not set a date for a hearing on the matter 
the violation occurred because the defendant failed to 
disclose the existence of oil and gas reserves having a value of 
approximately 1 billion the court ruling said 
the class action lawsuit was filed by the former shell minority 
shareholders against shell petroleum inc the royal dutchshell 
subsidiary that bought out shell oils minority shareholders in 
june 1985 
the anglodutch oil giant had owned 694 percent of shell oil 
it initially offered 55 a share for the remainder raised the bid 
to 58 and finally agreed to pay an extra 2 a share to settle a 
lawsuit by some minority shareholders 
the delaware trial was limited to the issue of whether adequate 
disclosure was made in materials sent to the former shell 
stockholders advising them of their option to accept the royal 
dutchshell offer or seek an appraisal of the fair value of their 
shares mcneil said 
hr hutchins a spokesman for houstonbased shell said the 
company was disappointed with the courts decision 
the court based its decision on an inadvertent error which 
left out about 8 percent of the discounted future net cash flow 
from estimated oil and gas reserves hutchins said 
the discounted cash flow analysis is soft data because it is 
based on numerous assumptions and estimates in view of the 
voluminous information that was furnished to the shareholders we 
believe they could readily have made an informed decision with 
respect to the 1985 merger proposal 
in a separate proceeding the same delaware court is determining 
the appraisal value of the shell oil stock for former owners of 1 
million shares who rejected the 60ashare offer these former 
owners have claimed the shares were worth up to 110 each 
</TEXT>
