<TEXT>
two ancient greek coins fetching more than a 
half million dollars each were among the record breakers tuesday at 
an auction of the highly touted coin and antique collections of the 
onetime billionaire hunt brothers 
the auction also saw the rare ides of march coin struck by 
brutus to commemorate the assassination of julius caesar in 44 
bc sell for 99000 
the items sold tuesday the first in a series of hunt auctions 
brought a total of just over 20 million far more than the 
presale estimate of 12 million 
a greek vase painted with a battle scene sold for a record 176 
million 
the 18inch vase circa 510 bc is black with red figures 
painted on it depicting the death of kyknos in battle with 
hercules it was reconstructed from a fragment signed by 
euphronius one of the most important ancient greek artists said 
sothebys david redden an expert in the field 
the buyer was identified only as a european dealer 
two silver greek coins became the most expensive ever sold at 
auction 
the decadrachm of agrigentum dating from 410 bc sold for 
572000 followed by another decadrachm circa 465 bc for 
528000 
the second coin had held the previous auction record having 
fetched 272000 in 1974 
all prices include the auction houses 10 percent commission 
the first coin sold tuesday is one of eight known specimens of 
its kind sothebys said it shows an eagle and four horses being 
driven by sun god helios on one side and two eagles perched over a 
dead hare on the other 
the other has the head of the goddess athena on one side and an 
owl on the other 
nelson bunker and william herbert hunt heirs to an oil fortune 
lost more than 15 billion speculating in the silver market a 
decade ago 
the dallas businessmen emerged from bankruptcy court protection 
earlier this year under a reorganization plan that called for them 
to sell off their antique collections and some personal possessions 
the new york auction has attracted collectors from around the 
world and was one of several planned in the coming year involving 
the hunt estates 
r carter pate trustee in charge of liquidating nelson bunker 
hunts estate said before tuesdays auction that he expected all 
of the asset sales to raise between 20 and 25 million 
most of the money will go to the internal revenue service the 
largest creditor in the brothers bankruptcy cases 
this weeks sale likely will be the most spectacular of the 
auctions because of the strength of the collection he said 
